ref=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1668.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Anyone else w/ this disorder?</span><hr size=1> I used to have similar mind-traps...haven't come back in years though.<br>
<br>
The first time I realized I was doin weird mental games it involved the need for symmetrical movement.  Every movement had to have an evenly counterbalancing movement, even if I was only imagining it.  So every time I reached for my pencil in school or scratched my ear or whatever I would go through a tic-tac-toe board of the 4 cardinal directions and 2 diagonals through the cross.  Always followed the same movement pattern every time.  The weirdest thing was I dont' know when I started, just one day I realized my head was bobbing around and then paid attention to what it was I was doing mentally.<br>
<br>
That one went away when I started counting.  I counted everything, cracks in walls, tiles on the floor, trees, syllables in words and sentences, lines on paper, etc.  Got to be pretty quick at it (and yeah was pretty good at math).  It got to the point that every sentence I spoke had to end on an even syllable, or I'd add words to make it fit.<br>
<br>
It got to where it interfered with daily life and conversation, etc like you describe...people just think you're weird if you dont' tell them what's going on.  If you do tell them they think you're crazy.<br>
<br>
The funny thing is, when I started playing music, it all stopped.  My brain started running songs all the time, which still goes on...I have constant background music, but that's a lot better than the other stuff.  So for a few years I was never bothered by my repetitive mindgames.  The summer after I graduated high school, I went in for a sinus operation.  I was laid up in bed for a few days recovering, and guess what?  I was drawing tic-tac-toe designs on the sheets with my fingers and counting ceiling dots the whole damn time.<br>
<br>
That's when I started thinking that maybe it's just a part of the brain that gets bored and starts running background subroutines, like a screensaver I guess.  Also from the people I've talked to who have experienced this type of thing, it seems more common in people of above-average intelligence.  So my bullshit theory on the matter is, smart people who aren't using their brains enough get bored I guess.  That supported by any psychobabble Stry?<br>
<br>
<br>
